<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Hello, my name is Extrah Dimensional of Povar.<P>I've read some goofy things on the mage balance list, which to me doesn't seem like balance at all.  Like pet graphics and pet names.  So I will address what I consider balance.<P>I've seen previous posts saying that mage pets are only marginally better than necro pets.  Which in some ways is true, but I think the poster looked at it the wrong way. I say this because the HPs between the two pets really can't be compared, since the two pets have totally different roles in a solo situation.  For one, the necro pet usually hits from behind--unless fear is resisted, and magician pets have to go toe  to toe with the mob, no matter what.  As far as the damage of the two pets, magician pets hit for generally the same damage each hit and swing just as much as the necro pets, and have pathetic spells that usually get resisted at higher levels (especially root hehe).  So yes, the magician pets are only marginally better than the necro pets, which brings me to the next point.<P>The necromancer and the magician are both widely considered to be soloing classes.  I don't mean to step on anyones toes when I say this, but necros don't really need a pet with huge amounts of HPs, since the only thing they have to worry about is resists with their fear spells and snares.  Combining that with mana regen and other types of spells, necros agreeably make much better soloers than magicians.  Why?  Because magicians get DD spells that aren't nearly as damaging as wizard spells (I can understand that) that are mostly fire based and sometimes magic based, and also have too high of a taunt to chain nuke.  Furthermore, we must then rely mainly on our pets (duh) to take and mostly deal the damage.  I wouldn't have a problem with any of that, except that I've noticed necromancers (among a few other classes as well, save that for another post hehe) are able to solo higher level mobs sooner than I or any other magicians can.  Don't agree with me?  Well then how is it that necromancers can take down things like Hill Giants or Griffins starting at level 34, and at level 39 I could barely manage to kill the same mobs with pet under 9% HP and me with zero mana? And after all that there's no way for me to regen my mana...and we have this HP regen spell that costs too many components, a spell which not only no other pure casters have, but that we don't need to regen HPs!  Because our pets tank not us!  Lastly, comparing mages with other solo classes, I personally don't see how they are all balanced.<P>Summary : We need our solo capability equal to the other solo classes.  Increasing DD spell damage wouldn't be the solution, since that wouldn't make wizards happy, and utility spells like root or snare just isn't our style (save that of the earth pet).  So the only thing left is to improve our pets.  Either increase HP considerably, or increase pets' damage.  Perhaps pets damage could be easily solved with the introduction of new summonable pet only procing weapons that do insane damage.  Increasing pet damage in huge amounts wouldn't be unbalancing I wouldn't think, since if the pet outdamages us (which it will, considering our DD spells) the pet soaks up about half the exp. I saw the proc weapon suggestion on the magician balance list, and it was on the "wish list".  Why is one of the seemingly most important suggestions only on the "wish list"?  I am interested in hearing some feedback, and please show your maturity and keep it polite  <IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/wink.gif">  Thanks for hearing me all the way through.
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
