<FONT SIZE="1" color="#000000" face="Verdana, Arial">
posted March 27, 2001 12:21 PM &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=280&t=000016&reply_num=000006&u="><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=280&t=000016&replyto=000006"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
First off, I *am* a newbie, I'm currently playing a lvl 24 (well, 23 thanks to Unrest) magician, and I do see a lot of strength as well as problems in the magician class.<P>First off, pets.  The main area of discussion in this post and a lot of other posts seems to be that necro pets are nearly as strong as mage pets.  This, I would have to agree with.  Although a mage pet will beat a necro pet, that doesn't really say anything at all about in-game play.  Just because my pet can beat your pet doesn't make me the stronger class.  This is especially true when you consider that pets are supposed to be one of the mages' main offensive weapons.<P>Now, I may not have a lot of experience in game, but I've done my fair share of grouping with necros and I have to say that in combat it seems the necro does a lot more damage than I do.  This situation is this: I re-summon until I get a pet that is strong; the necro summons once.  In battle, my pet bashes and double attacks for 22; the necro pet kicks and double attacks for 20.  Now, of course my pet has special procs and despite what everyone else says I don't really notice any slow down when they're in the middle of combat and cast, but if necro pets get procs in the later levels as well, then that takes away from the uniqueness of our pets somewhat.  Yes, our pets proc at low levels, but if other classes' pets proc as well then it shouldn't really be touted as one of our special abilities.<P>Going further in the mage vs. necro discussion, at least in the low levels it's somewhat unbalanced.  For example, one time I was in a group and among our numbers was a lvl 24 necro.  Throughout the battles, I would have to manuever around to use my Bolt of Flame spell.  Meanwhile, the necro would stand in the back and cast Shock of Poison.  According to him, this spell hits for 176 then DoTs.  176 and a DoT!!  When I was briefly 24, I cast Shock of Something for 158.  Now, to me, even without the pets it seems the necro is out-damaging me, but I thought we were supposed to be the most offensively capable class in the game?  I'd have to disagree with this statement though - I have seen way too many lvl 20+ warriors in Highhold Keep smacking monsters for 100+ several times in a round.<P>Actually, I feel safe saying that a lot of other classes are given priority in game over mages (grouping-wise).  When they say nobody wants a mage, they are oh so right.  What people would rather have is a tank, a healer, or an enchanter.  I don't think I've ever seen someone shouting, looking for a nuker or a mage.  But I still keep playing away because a) I'm addicted; and b) I hope one day the magician class will be fixed.  Until then, regardless of how powerful it is, it's something I enjoy playing.<P>Another point I would like to make is that I feel it is very unfair for pets to take 50% of the exp if they deal the majority of the damage.  If pets were just something nice they decided to throw in, it would be different, but as I stated before pets are our main offensive weapon!  This would be akin to penalizing a wizard for using his best nukes, or penalizing a necro for DoTing or whatever.  It is really the only feasible way to solo for us.  I'm aware that in a group situation the penalty drops to taking 1% of the group's exp, but I feel 50% soloing is unjustified.  Perhaps in the higher levels you guys don't have this problem, but there are times when you can't find a single *good* group.  Sometimes you just can't find one and have to go it on your own.<P>Suffice it to say, I feel our class should revolve around our pets.  Hell, the EQ manual describes the mage as "the summoner of the arcane arts."  Very rarely do I receive requests for anything to be summoned other than bread and water.  Bread and water!!  C'mon now, I'm supposed to have all these awesome conjuration spells at my fingertips and they ask for food and drink.  Occasionally I receive requests for arrows or throwing daggers, when a melee feels like practicing.  The problem is, our other item summons are crap.  I'm lvl 24, and I give my pet summoned daggers, when I hit 29 I may give him swords of runes (depending on the situation).  At 39, I will give him mystic daggers.  And thus concludes the mage strategy guide - that was it.  What I would like to see is newer, more useful summons.  Upgrade that dinky throwing dagger to proc shock of blades!  Give us some melee weapons that are useful!<P>Another point is pet damage.  I realize we can't have pets dealing damage like players do, because that would severely unbalance the game - but people talk about how our pets deal damage and, really, its insignificant.  Say at 24 my pet quads for 26 - 104 damage, not bad, not bad.  Until you see the warrior quad for 50+ that is.  Now, I'm not trying to steal the warriors spotlight, but this is supposed to be a significant source of our damage?<P>Anyway, I could go on and on.  My main point is that we're supposed to be these bad-ass summoners, and we're not.  I don't care about other classes getting pets, but I think ours should shine above all the others.  What would make me happy (and probably not many other people) would to see the magician lose some of his nuking capability in exchange for better summons.  Then I would like to see our item summonings to get upgraded at later levels so that we have something more useful than bread and water.  Pet variety would be a plus as well.  This would, I feel, make magicians truly unique.  We wouldn't be just one of many pet classes, or one of many nuking classes.  We'd be something unique and interesting to play, and this potential added utility use might actually make us desireable for grouping!<P>Just some of my thoughts.<P>Isorashi<BR>23 (Soon to be 24! Damn you Unrest!) magician<BR>The Seventh Hammer
</FONT>
